  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a jointly owned Brisbane property when a relationship has ended is one of the more common and more complex situations a real estate agent encounters. It is common because property is often the largest shared asset in any relationship and eventually needs to be dealt with. It is complex because the legal framework around it is not purely a conveyancing matter. Federal family law intersects with Queensland property law in ways that catch many separating couples by surprise, sometimes mid-campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The two pathways to sell</h2>
      <p>There are essentially two ways a jointly owned property gets sold after separation. The first is by consent: both parties agree to sell and agree on how the proceeds will be divided. The second is by court order: one party applies to the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia for an order that requires the sale and specifies how the proceeds are distributed.</p>

      <p>The consent pathway is simpler, faster, and less expensive. Both parties sign the Form 6 agency authority, both sign the contract when it comes, and both sign the settlement documents. The practical requirement is that both parties are cooperating and can communicate clearly enough to work through those steps. A binding financial agreement or consent orders registered with the court should formalise the proceeds split before or at settlement, rather than leaving it as an informal understanding. Informal agreements about proceeds, however clearly understood between the parties, create exposure that formal documentation closes off.</p>

      <p>The court order pathway is available when one party refuses to cooperate, cannot be located, or when the parties cannot reach agreement on terms. An application to the Federal Circuit and Family Court for a property settlement order can include a specific order requiring the property to be sold and directing how the net proceeds are to be divided. This process takes longer and costs more, but it provides the legal certainty required to proceed when consent is absent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why informal agreements are risky</h2>
      <p>Some separating couples assume that a handshake understanding about who gets what is good enough. It is not. In Queensland, property division claims can be reopened for up to 12 months after a divorce is finalised. For de facto couples, the window is generally two years after the date of separation. A sale that proceeds without consent orders or a binding financial agreement leaves the door open for either party to come back and contest the division of proceeds during that period, even after the money has been spent.</p>

      <p>Formalising the agreement through consent orders or a binding financial agreement is not about distrust. It is about finality. Once those documents are in place, the division of proceeds is legally settled and cannot be relitigated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a real estate agent can and cannot do</h2>
      <p>A real estate agent is not a legal advisor and cannot resolve disputes between co-owners. The agent's role is to act on the instructions of the authorised sellers. In Queensland, both joint owners must sign the Form 6 agency authority before an agent can legally list the property. If one party refuses to sign, the agent cannot proceed. An agent who acts on instructions from only one joint owner exposes themselves and their agency to significant legal liability.</p>

      <p>This means that if there is a dispute about whether to sell, or about the terms of a sale, that dispute needs to be resolved through legal channels before the agent is contacted. Calling an agent first and hoping the other party will eventually come around is a path that regularly leads to wasted time, aborted campaigns, and in some cases legal costs that reduce the proceeds available to both parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The right sequence before you list</h2>
      <p>The sequence that consistently produces the best outcomes is this: engage a family law solicitor before you engage a real estate agent. The solicitor's role is to confirm the legal pathway you are on, ensure the proceeds division is documented appropriately, and advise on whether consent orders or a binding financial agreement is more suitable for your circumstances.</p>

      <p>Once the legal framework is confirmed and both parties have signed the necessary documents, the real estate process proceeds normally. Both parties will need to sign the agency authority, the contract, and the settlement documents. If one party has moved out of Brisbane or is difficult to contact, arrangements for remote signing or the grant of a specific power of attorney for settlement purposes may need to be made in advance.</p>

      <p>A conveyancer or solicitor handling the conveyancing should also be briefed on the family law context from the outset. This allows them to flag any issues with the title, the ownership structure, or the settlement instructions before exchange rather than at the point where a problem costs money to fix.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains tax and transfers between separating spouses</h2>
      <p>One aspect of a separation-related sale that deserves specific attention is the capital gains tax treatment of any transfers between the parties. In certain circumstances, a transfer of property between separating spouses or de facto partners under a formal court order or binding financial agreement may qualify for a CGT rollover or exemption under federal tax law, effectively deferring or reducing the CGT liability that would otherwise arise.</p>

      <p>The eligibility conditions for these concessions are specific and worth understanding before any transfer takes place. A tax adviser should be consulted before the property is transferred or sold, not after. The timing and structure of the transaction can affect the available concessions significantly, and decisions made in haste during an already stressful process can have tax consequences that outlast the sale by several years.</p>

